parameters.source_text:
Case 2-3
Infertility Treatment: God's Will?
Bette Gabriele had struggled with obesity most of her adult life. She lost
and gained 100 pounds at least twice. When she finally found a healthy
combination of diet and exercise, she was almost 30. A year later she met
Gino, the man she would marry. For the past six years the Garbrieles have
tried to conceive. Both were fully evaluated at an infertility center. Test re-
sults indicated that the Gabrieles have unexplained infertility, although
Bette’s age and weight gain since her marriage were risk factors in the de-
velopment of infertility.
As a practicing Catholic, Ms. Gabriele spoke to her priest, who said
there were no church objections to drugs to induce ovarian hyperstimulation
(OH) or timed intercourse. In vitro fertilization (IVF) and intrauterine insemi-
nation (IUI) were not permitted. If any treatment resulted in multiple preg-
nancies, reduction of the number of embryos, a common recommendation,
would be forbidden as it would be seen as abortion according to Church
teaching.
Ms. Gabriele began OH treatment but did not become pregnant during
her first cycle. She was discouraged because of her efforts and of the signifi-
cant expense. A friend who was going through the same treatment decided
to terminate further treatment after IVF failure. She told Ms. Gabriele, “You
just have to accept the reality that technology doesn’t work all the time.”
With her husband's encouragement, Ms. Gabriele decided to continue
treatment. The next month, hope loomed on the horizon. Studies showed
there were multiple mature follicles indicating a good chance of a multife-
tal pregnancy, thus increasing the risks to the fetuses and herself if she
carried all of the babies to delivery.
She felt like time was running out, so she opted to proceed, saying to
herself that whatever happened was God's will.

data.vignette: A 37-year-old woman with unexplained infertility has tried to conceive for six years. She is in her second cycle of ovarian stimulation with timed intercourse. Today’s ultrasound shows many mature follicles, more than expected for her dose. You worry that conception this cycle could lead to a high-order multifetal pregnancy, with serious risks for her and any fetuses. She and her husband understand this. She says she is willing to accept whatever happens and adds that, for religious reasons, she would not consider selective fetal reduction if a multifetal pregnancy occurs. She is exhausted by years of treatment and the out-of-pocket cost of each cycle. The ovulation trigger is due tonight, so the plan must be set now. Clinic policy and state law allow either proceeding or canceling the cycle in this situation.
data.choice_1: Proceed with the trigger and timed intercourse as requested
data.choice_2: Cancel the cycle and instruct strict avoidance of intercourse

neutralize_clinical_considerations.suggested_changes: Remove language that makes the cancellation option sound medically mandatory. Rephrase “You worry that conception this cycle could lead to a high-order multifetal pregnancy” to a more neutral framing such as: “This level of response raises concern for a multifetal pregnancy; multifetal gestations can carry increased maternal and neonatal complications.” Avoid implying the clinician’s option is the medically ‘correct’ one by adding that outcomes are uncertain and that both approaches are used in practice. Also consider adding that some clinicians proceed with close counseling while others cancel to reduce the chance of multiples.

key_information.suggested_changes: Specify the clinically relevant details that drive the dilemma and remove/trim others. Add: approximate number of mature follicles and estradiol level range (without exact numbers if possible) or qualitatively “numerous mature follicles and very high estradiol,” and whether she is using gonadotropins vs oral agents. Clarify whether conversion to IVF is possible/available or not (and why not), and whether coasting or dose adjustment is feasible today. Trim: “more than expected for her dose” is vague; replace with a concrete qualitative descriptor. Keep religion/finances because they affect the ethical stakes.

clinical_plausibility.suggested_changes: Make the reproductive endocrinology details realistic and internally consistent. High-order multifetal risk is much more typical with gonadotropin stimulation; timed intercourse with ‘many mature follicles’ would usually prompt strong counseling and cancellation, or IVF conversion if available. Clarify the medication type (e.g., injectable gonadotropins), monitoring findings, and that cancellation involves withholding hCG trigger and advising abstinence/condoms. Consider adding that IUI was planned/possible (common in these cycles), or explicitly state why IVF conversion is not feasible (e.g., no insurance coverage, lab capacity, or patient declines).

non_triviality.suggested_changes: As written, canceling appears clearly safer/standard, making the choice feel one-sided. To make both options defensible, add ethically and clinically relevant counterweights: e.g., patient has diminished ovarian reserve/advanced reproductive age concerns, has had multiple canceled cycles, limited ability to afford another cycle, and understands increased multiple-gestation risks; note that even with many follicles, conception is not guaranteed. Alternatively, narrow the clinical scenario so the risk is increased but not extreme (e.g., ‘several’ mature follicles rather than ‘many’) so proceeding is a plausible option rather than near-mandatory cancellation.

decision_equipoise.suggested_changes: Rebalance the vignette so canceling is not an ethically/clinically obvious default. (1) Add concrete, qualitative harms of cancellation that a reasonable clinician would weigh heavily: e.g., this is her last covered/affordable cycle (coverage ends next month), she cannot repeat stimulation for many months, and delaying materially threatens her chance at pregnancy at age 37. (2) Make the multifetal risk serious but not portrayed as near-certain: replace 'many mature follicles' with language like 'several more mature follicles than expected' and clarify that high-order multiples are a real possibility but not inevitable. (3) Add that mitigation options short of cancellation are unavailable tonight (e.g., no capacity for urgent conversion to IVF or medication adjustment), so the binary choice is truly forced. These edits preserve nonmaleficence concerns while making autonomy/beneficence-to-the-patient (a chance at pregnancy) a comparably weighty countervailing consideration.

ethical_neutrality.suggested_changes: Remove or balance language that frames one option as obviously responsible (e.g., “high-order,” “serious risks,” “exhausted”). Rephrase to neutral clinical terms: “risk of multifetal gestation with associated maternal and neonatal morbidity.” Add a parallel statement of the harms of cancellation (emotional/financial burden, treatment delay) in similarly clinical language.

conciseness_coherence.suggested_changes: Tighten and clarify key clinical details driving the dilemma: specify approximate follicle count range (without exact numbers if you want) or at least “numerous ≥16–18 mm follicles,” and whether estradiol is elevated; clarify whether IVF conversion is feasible today. Remove redundant phrases (“she and her husband understand this”). Keep only details that alter ethical stakes (cost, religious objection to reduction, urgency of trigger tonight).

choice_brevity.suggested_changes: Shorten to ~10–15 words and keep action-only, no extra context. Example: Choice 1: “Administer trigger and proceed with timed intercourse this cycle.” Choice 2: “Withhold trigger, cancel cycle, and advise abstinence/contraception this week.”

balanced_difficulty.suggested_changes: As written, the vignette implies an unusually high risk of high-order multiples (“many mature follicles…high‑order multifetal pregnancy, with serious risks”), making cancellation feel like the medically/ethically safer default and therefore lopsiding the dilemma. To rebalance: (1) Specify the follicle findings are borderline rather than extreme (e.g., ‘3–4 mature follicles and several intermediate follicles’ rather than ‘many’), and explicitly state why the clinician thinks the risk is meaningfully increased but not clearly unacceptable. (2) Add a countervailing cost to cancellation beyond disappointment/expense—e.g., she will lose a limited authorization window, has a narrow time off work to attempt treatment, or has a medical reason this cycle is uniquely favorable—so proceeding has a defensible beneficence rationale. (3) Avoid language that presumes a likely “high‑order” outcome; instead describe the concern as a credible possibility without implying it is the expected result.

exhaustive_binary_options.suggested_changes: The binary is not exhaustive because several realistic middle paths exist in ovarian stimulation: convert to IVF with elective single-embryo transfer, convert to IUI with modified timing, ‘coast’/delay trigger, reduce/withhold trigger and re-scan tomorrow, or proceed with trigger but recommend abstinence/barrier contraception rather than ‘strict avoidance’ as the only alternative. To make it truly binary, explicitly rule these out with concrete constraints, e.g., ‘the IVF lab is unavailable/they have not completed IVF consent and cannot start IVF this cycle,’ ‘the follicles are already at size where delaying trigger increases OHSS risk,’ and ‘there is no time for another ultrasound/medication adjustment before the trigger window closes tonight.’ Then frame the choice as only: trigger with intercourse vs cancel with clear instructions to avoid conception.

no_guideline_override.suggested_changes: Fertility societies (e.g., ASRM) have widely used cycle-cancellation thresholds for ovulation induction when multiple mature follicles develop, specifically to reduce multifetal gestation; many clinics treat cancellation as standard of care when follicle counts exceed certain limits. As written, the vignette does not explain why such standards do not settle the decision, so ‘cancel’ risks being the guideline-concordant answer. To fix: (1) State the follicle number/size falls into an area where guidelines are permissive or conflicting (e.g., just at/near a cutoff, or different guidance for timed intercourse vs IUI). (2) Alternatively, explicitly note the clinic’s written protocol leaves discretion in this exact scenario and that both proceeding and canceling are considered acceptable practice locally. (3) Clarify the patient-specific factors that make strict guideline application ethically contestable (e.g., prior cycle history, limited future access), without making either option reckless.

data.vignette: A 37-year-old woman with unexplained infertility has tried to conceive for six years. She is using injectable gonadotropins with timed intercourse. Today’s ultrasound shows four mature follicles and several intermediate follicles. Her hormone levels are higher than typical for this protocol. This response raises concern for a multifetal pregnancy, which can increase maternal complications and preterm neonatal morbidity. Pregnancy is still uncertain, and some clinicians proceed in borderline cycles after counseling while others cancel to limit the chance of multiples. She says she accepts the possibility of multiples and, for religious reasons, would not consider selective fetal reduction. Canceling would mean losing her last authorized, affordable cycle because her coverage ends next month and she cannot take more time off work until then. The ovulation trigger is due tonight. The IVF lab cannot accommodate conversion this cycle, and there is no time for additional monitoring or dose adjustment. Clinic policy and state law allow either approach in this situation.
data.choice_1: Give the trigger and proceed with timed intercourse this cycle
data.choice_2: Withhold the trigger, cancel the cycle, and advise abstinence or barrier contraception
